  "prompt": "What is the formula used to calculate thermal energy and how is it calculated?",
  "response": "Thermal energy, in the context of heat transfer, is often calculated using the formula related to specific heat capacity, which is:\n\n\\[ Q = mc\\Delta T \\]\n\nwhere:\n\n- \\( Q \\) is the amount of thermal energy (in joules, J).\n- \\( m \\) is the mass of the substance (in kilograms, kg).\n- \\( c \\) is the specific heat capacity of the substance (in joules per kilogram per degree Celsius, J/kg\u00b0C).\n- \\( \\Delta T \\) is the change in temperature (in degrees Celsius, \u00b0C).\n\nHere's how you calculate it:\n\n1. **Determine the mass \\( m \\)** of the substance you are interested in.\n2. **Find the specific heat capacity \\( c \\)** of the substance. This is a property of the material and can be found in tables or literature.\n3. **Measure the change in temperature \\( \\Delta T \\)**, which is the difference between the final temperature and the initial temperature (`\u0394T = T_final - T_initial`).\n\nOnce you have these values, you multiply them together to find the thermal energy \\( Q \\).\n\n### Example Calculation\n\nLet's say you have a 2 kg block of aluminum (specific heat capacity \\( c \\approx 900 \\ \\text{J/kg\u00b0C} \\)) and you want to calculate the thermal energy required to raise its temperature from 20\u00b0C to 50\u00b0C.\n\n1. **Mass \\( m \\)**: 2 kg\n2. **Specific heat capacity \\( c \\)**: 900 J/kg\u00b0C\n3. **Temperature change \\( \\Delta T \\)**: \\( 50\u00b0C - 20\u00b0C = 30\u00b0C \\)\n\nUsing the formula:\n\n\\( Q = mc\\Delta T \\)\n\n\\( Q = 2 \\ \\text{kg} \\times 900 \\ \\text{J/kg\u00b0C} \\times 30 \\ \\text{\u00b0C} \\)\n\n\\( Q = 54000 \\ \\text{J} \\)\n\nSo, 54,000 joules of thermal energy are required to raise the temperature of the 2 kg block of aluminum from 20\u00b0C to 50\u00b0C.",
